File: A man wearing a face mask as a preventive measure against the COVID-19 coronavirus stands on an escalator outside of a shopping mall in Beijing on March 11, 2020. GENEVA - The World Health Organization sees the outbreak of the new coronavirus as a pandemic, Director General Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus said on Wednesday. READ:Â Coronavirus: How big, how bad, and what to look out for "We are deeply concerned both by the alarming levels of spread and severity and by the alarming levels of inaction. We have therefore made the assessment that COVID-19 can be characterised as a pandemic," he told a news conference. In South Africa, Health Minister Zweli Mkhize confirmed six new cases of COVID-19 in the country, outside of the group of 10 people who returned from Italy. According to a statement released by the Health Department, four cases are in Gauteng, one is in KwaZulu-Natal and one in the Western Cape.